6e4a8-2 | 2026-05-31T01:20:19Z | session:6e4a880c-8e83-4ef2-a336-646e335aa6f1 | Assistant: I found the bug. In `ReportsTabView.swift`, there are two `.sheet(isPresented:)` modifiers chained on the same view on lines 128 and 141. In SwiftUI, only the last sheet modifier works — which means the HTML report sheet (first) is silently swallowed, so HTML/bundle reports like "Command Center" never open. [...] Let me fix this by replacing both sheet modifiers with a single `.sheet(item:)` using a unified selection type. \n  [...] **Root cause:** `ReportsTabView.swift` (lines 128 & 141) had two `.sheet(isPresented:)` modifiers chained on the same view — one for HTML reports, one for markdown. In SwiftUI, when you chain multiple `.sheet()` modifiers, **only the last one is active**. The markdown sheet (second) was overriding the HTML sheet (first), so HTML bundle reports like "Command Center" silently did nothing when tapped. \n 
8c920-1 | 2026-05-31T01:20:35Z | session:8c920ed8-b5c1-45df-8b23-c89cd3990646 | Assistant: Now I understand the flow. The issue is in `composerTrailingActionButton`: when the user hits send while dictation is recording, it calls `sendMessage()` directly, but recording hasn't stopped yet. The `onChange(.idle)` handler will then also call `sendMessage()` — potential double-send. The fix is to just stop recording when the button is tapped during dictation; the existing `onChange(.idle)` handler already sends whatever was transcribed. \n  \n Assistant: Here's what changed and why: \n  \n - **During recording**: tapping the button now calls `stopRecording()` instead of `sendMessage()`. The existing `onChange(of: dictationManager.state)` handler already fires when state goes `.idle` and calls `sendMessage()` with whatever was transcribed — so there's no double-send and no separate code path needed. \n - **Button label**: shows the send arrow (filled circle) whenever recording is active, so the user sees it as "tap to stop & send" — even before any text has been transcribed. [...] - **Button label**: shows the send arrow (filled circle) whenever recording is active, so the user sees it as "tap to stop & send" — even before any text has been transcribed. \n - **`disabled` logic**: the button is never disabled while recording, so users can always tap to stop. [...] - **`disabled` logic**: the button is never disabled while recording, so users can always tap to stop.
3d0ab-1 | 2026-05-31T01:20:57Z | session:3d0ab623-c663-4728-a8ff-a3a77b91e45a | Assistant: I found the bug from code analysis — no logs needed. When ElevenLabs commits a VAD segment with `isFinal=true`, it sends the committed text, which is often **shorter** than the running cumulative partial (the partial runs ahead of the VAD boundary). The current code uses `result.text` directly, so the display jumps backwards. \n  \n Example: \n - Partial builds up: `"hello world how are you"` → displayed ✓ \n - `isFinal=true, text="hello world"` (segment commit, shorter than partial) \n - `accumulatedText = "hello world"`, `currentSegmentText = ""` \n - Display drops to `"hello world"` — this is the "restart" the user sees \n  \n The fix: when the final is shorter than the accumulated partial, prefer the longer one (our partial is a better estimate until the new segment catches up).
