a1119-2 | 2026-05-31T01:21:30Z | session:a11196a4-22c4-4c28-be5d-bd27c6de1632 | Your name: developer (5233e312) [...] Assistant: I have a clear picture of the bug. The ElevenLabs API with `commit_strategy=vad` doesn't send `is_final=true` when VAD detects a pause mid-sentence — it just silently resets its partial transcript. So when the new partial arrives after the pause, `accumulatedText` is still empty, and the display restarts from just the new words. [...]  \n The fix: track the current VAD segment's partial text separately, and detect a new segment when the incoming partial doesn't extend the previous one — then commit the previous partial to `accumulatedText` before continuing. \n  [...] The fix: track the current VAD segment's partial text separately, and detect a new segment when the incoming partial doesn't extend the previous one — then commit the previous partial to `accumulatedText` before continuing. \n  [...] **Fix:** Added `currentSegmentText` to track the running partial within the current VAD segment. When a new partial arrives that doesn't extend the current segment text (`hasPrefix` check), it means ElevenLabs started a new segment — we commit the old segment text to `accumulatedText` before continuing. The display always shows `accumulatedText + currentSegmentText`, so pausing mid-sentence no longer loses the prior words.
